Mandatory microchipping proposed for cats and dogs
Kęstutis Mažeika, Chairman of the Environmental Protection Committee of the Seimas, together with other members of the Seimas, registered amendments to the Animal Welfare and Protection Act, which propose the mandatory marking of cats and dogs with subcutaneous microchips.
'We propose that microchipping of cats and dogs should be compulsory and that registration and marking should be organised by local authorities, the Ministry of Agriculture and the State Food and Veterinary Service.
In 2019, all dogs will be tagged free of charge with state funds, and in 2020, cats will also be tagged, so residents will not have to worry and the costs will be covered by specially provided state funding", said Kęstutis Mažeika, Chairman of the Seimas Environmental Protection Committee.
The amendments to the law aim to address the systemic need for pet labelling.
It is hoped that this will help to prevent problems caused by irresponsible breeders, illegal breeders or sellers.
It is provisionally estimated that the expected average cost of the microchip and the service, which will be around EUR 5, will compensate all animal owners during the transitional period.
The total cost of tagging all pet animals can be up to EUR 6 million.
This appropriation is intended to cover expenditure on studies, meetings of experts, information and publications directly linked to the achievement of the objective of the programme or measures coming under this article, and any other expenditure on technical and administrative assistance not involving public authority tasks outsourced by the Commission under ad hoc service contracts.
It is anticipated that the labelling programmes will be funded through the Municipal Environmental Support Special Programme, whose revenues will increase significantly this year due to increased taxes on natural resources and reallocation of funds.
In addition to marking cats and dogs, municipalities will be able to use the funds for spaying and neutering and other programs.
According to Mr Mažeika, the practice of compulsory tagging is widespread in almost all European Union countries, which protects both the animals themselves (because lost ones can easily be returned to their owners) and saves the time of the animal breeders themselves, who have to spend a lot of time and money searching for a stray and lost pet.
In addition, EU legislation requires that only tagged pets are allowed to travel.
At the same time, the label imposes a responsibility to care for the animal throughout its life.
Previous proposals for compulsory labelling have been met with resistance as the programmes were proposed to be publicly funded.
'The current model should avoid this criticism, as it proposes to finance animal welfare through increased revenues in the environmental support programme and by granting the right to mark not only to veterinarians, but also to members of the public, i.e. persons from animal welfare institutions who have completed special courses at the Veterinary Academy,' say the authors of the draft.
The draft law was registered by a group of members of the Seimas representing different factions of the Seimas - Kęstutis Mažeika, Algimantas Dumbrava, Eugenijus Gentvilis, Edmundas Pupinis, Rimas Andrikis, Antanas Vinkus and others.
