Restrictions on cogeneration plants challenged before the Constitutional Court
As promised, the opposition in the Seimas appealed to the Constitutional Court (CC) against the ruling party's decision to adopt a law on the possibility of suspending the construction of waste incineration plants.
On Tuesday, the opposition Homeland Union-Lithuanian Christian Democrats (TS-LKD) faction in the Seimas announced that a group of members of the Seimas had appealed to the Constitutional Court to investigate the constitutionality of the amendments to the Waste Management Act adopted by the ruling party.
'Parliamentarians emphasise that the provisions of the law aim to question the existing waste incineration plant projects by instructing the Government to set new limits (20 km distance from the residential area) for waste incineration plants to be built in Vilnius and Kaunas before the law comes into force,' the report says.
'Parliamentarians note that the wording of the prohibition on the construction of waste management facilities of national importance (i.e. the distance and definition of the concept of 'residential area') in the Act leads to the conclusion that this prohibition disproportionately restricts or even denies the very essence of the right to engage in economic activities related to the incineration of waste for energy production, as the criteria laid down are formulated in such a way that, given the density and distribution of the population in Lithuania, it would be practically impossible to build such facilities throughout the country,' it adds.
The application alleges that the law is contrary to the constitutional principle of the rule of law.
'KT has repeatedly pointed out that legislation does not apply to legal facts and effects which occurred before the entry into force of the newly adopted legislation.
In this case, the Government is empowered to apply the law retroactively on the basis of an unspecified criterion.
The constitutional principles of legal certainty, legal certainty, protection of legitimate expectations and thus the constitutional principle of the rule of law are violated by the introduction of such a legal regulation,' the appeal states.
It also notes that significant financial investments have already been made in the Vilnius and Kaunas CHP projects.
If the current projects were to be stopped, the state would not only suffer hundreds of millions in financial losses, but the population of Lithuania would also suffer huge losses - increased heating costs and increased environmental pollution due to the growing amount of waste disposal in landfills.
The appeal to the Constitutional Tribunal was signed by Algirdas Butkevičius, Deputy Chairman of the TS-LKD, Liberal Movement, Social Democratic and ruling Social Democratic Labour Parties in the Seimas.
A couple of weeks ago, the ruling Seimas managed to muster 71 votes to override President Dalia Grybauskaitė's veto of amendments to the Waste Management Act, which gave the government the right to stop the construction of cogeneration plants that had already begun, as well as to establish a "quarantine" zone 20 km from residential areas for the construction of such plants.
The amendments to the law re-adopted by the Sejm will enter into force on 1 January 2019.
