The health agency ANSES announced that the decision to ban all products containing the pesticide metam followed a new safety inspection launched earlier this year, even before at least three waves of poisonings began in September in the department of Maine-et-Loire.
Because of these cases, the government had already suspended the use of the pesticide.
This soil disinfectant chemical should not come into contact with plants or farm workers.
To be effective, the product must be used in large quantities.
Approximately 700 tons were used annually in France.
At least 70 people, including many farm workers, complained of eye and throat problems and respiratory problems in the region of Angers, where lettuce sultanas are grown.
"These episodes confirm the correctness of our decision, but they have not precipitated it", ANSES deputy director Francoise Weber told the newspaper Ouest France on Monday.
One of the most widely used pesticides in the United States and Europe, metam, is listed by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) as a "probable human carcinogen".
The pesticide, sold under names such as Vapam and Sectagon, is authorised in Europe until 2022, when a new safety assessment must be carried out.
"There was no choice but to withdraw it from the market, regardless of whether there were alternatives", Weber told the newspaper.
'We understand the difficulties that will arise for lettuce growers, for farmers in general, but public health is more important,' she said.
Farmers have already expressed their dissatisfaction with the government's decision last month to suspend the use of metam in a region whose economy is heavily dependent on intensive agriculture.
This region near Nantes produces more than half of the 35 000 tonnes of lettuce broth consumed annually in Europe.
There will be "a lot less sultanas, radishes and leeks" next season after the government banned the use of metam last month, Philippe Retiere, head of the Nantes growers' federation, told AFP.
