Exercises to respond to extreme flooding in Lithuania
In Lithuania, a ten-day exercise to improve the authorities' response to extreme flooding begins on Monday.
According to the Department of Fire Protection and Rescue (PAGD), the exercise will test the readiness of state institutions to work in the country in the event of a national emergency such as a flood: to eliminate its consequences, to coordinate the search, rescue and emergency evacuation of people from flooded areas, to organize their supply of drinking water, food, to ensure the necessary energy supply and to take other measures to protect the population.
The exercise will involve more than 100 representatives from all ministries and other institutions in the country, as well as members of the 12 municipal emergency operations centres.
The preparatory phase of the exercise will take place from 5 to 13 November, during which the municipalities will decide on the management of the emergency situation based on the information received from the PAGD from the Hydrometeorological Service about continuous rainfall and the onset of flooding.
The active phase of the exercise is scheduled for 14-15 November.
The State Emergency Operations Centre will operate in the department and the Institutional Emergency Operations Centres in state and municipal institutions.
Following the declaration by the Government of a State of Emergency due to the effects of the floods, the Head of Operations appointed by the Prime Minister will lead the liquidation of the emergency situation, the elimination of its consequences, the protection and rescue of people and property.
According to Mindaugas Kanapickas, deputy director of PAGD, the main purpose of the exercise is to check the readiness of the institutions to carry out the functions provided for in the legislation, to assess the possibilities of exchanging information, to check how prepared the population, state and municipal institutions, institutions and enterprises are to warn and inform about the impending disaster, and to "improve the emergency management skills of state institutions".
The exercise will also demonstrate the joint capabilities of Lithuanian, Latvian and Estonian fire and rescue services to pump large volumes of water out of flooded areas.
The BalticFloodCombat module was set up in 2009 for this purpose.
