Irish Prime Minister Leo Varadkar promised to consider the proposal but ruled out any possibility of Britain unilaterally withdrawing from the agreement, according to a statement released by the Irish government.
In the conversation, Mrs May 'raised the possibility of reviewing the hedging mechanism', it said.
'Varadkar has indicated that he is open to reviewing the new proposals, provided that the outcome of such a review does not involve a unilateral decision to lift the safeguard measures,' the government said in a statement.
Brexit negotiators are struggling to find an acceptable solution to avoid checks at the land border between the UK and Ireland when Britain leaves the single market and customs union next March.
The two sides agree on 'safeguard measures' to keep the border between the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland open pending a wider trade agreement to ensure that additional customs checks are not carried out at the border.
The EU wants Northern Ireland to continue to abide by EU customs rules, but London wants them to apply temporarily to the whole of the UK.
The Daily Telegraph reported on Monday that Brexit Secretary Dominic Raab wants Britain to be able to unilaterally withdraw from the backstop in three months.
However, Varadkar told reporters in Dublin that his government "cannot support this".
"Three-month or limited-term hedging instruments are not worth the paper they are written on", he stated.
Earlier, London and Brussels denied reports of a breakthrough in Brexit negotiations after reports emerged in Britain over the weekend that an agreement was within reach.
