A group of prominent thinkers, including Nobel laureates, issued a declaration on Monday calling for the right to reliable information in the Internet age.
Among the 25 signatories of the International Declaration on Information and Democracy are economists Amartya Sen and Joseph Stiglitz, Iranian lawyer and human rights activist Shirin Ebadi, winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, and writer Mario Vargas Llosa, winner of the Nobel Prize for Literature.
"We urge leaders of goodwill on all continents to take action to strengthen democratic models and open public debate in which citizens can make decisions based on facts", the group said in a statement.
They argue that the "global information and communications space" is a common good that "must be protected in order to strengthen freedom of expression and opinion".
"People have a fundamental right to information that is freely gathered, processed and disseminated, based on the principles of a commitment to truth, pluralism of views and rational methods of fact-finding", the declaration added.
The document asks for help from world leaders, including US President Donald Trump, who is often critical of 'fake news' but is regularly accused of distorting facts.
World leaders should take a stand on the issue when they meet at the Paris Peace Forum from 11 to 13 November, urged the signatories.
The declaration was drafted over a two-month period under the direction of Ebadi and Christophe Deloire, head of Reporters Without Borders (RSF), a Paris-based organisation that defends media freedom and journalists' rights.
Other signatories include former Senegalese President Abdou Diouf, Chinese lawyer and human rights activist Teng Biao, and political scientist Francis Fukuyama.
Parliament approves higher fines for harmful products
The Seimas approved amendments to the Law on Product Safety providing for increased fines for violations of product safety.
The amendments were approved unanimously in the Chamber.
As Antanas Vinkus, a member of the Parliamentary Health Committee, said about the new draft, it is welcome that the objectives are related to better consumer protection of products.
In addition, its provisions are adapted to the requirements of the Decision of the European Parliament and of the Council.
'My head, in the proposed draft law are distributed more precisely and specifically to all actors involved in the supply and distribution process: manufacturers, service providers, importers, distributors and others.
Practice shows that the current system of fines does not always prevent further infringements, as those who have paid the fines continue to commit repeated infringements,' said Mr Vinkus.
The draft was drawn up by the Ministry of Economy and, after approval by the Government, supplemented by the Economic Committee of the Seimas.
The amendments to the law aim to increase penalties for infringements, strengthen consumer protection, give more powers to market surveillance authorities and create a clear system for monitoring and enforcing product safety requirements.
According to the Ministry of Economy, there is currently no obligation for producers to label the product properly to ensure its traceability.
Moreover, according to the Ministry, market surveillance authorities are not granted the right to enter the territory, buildings, premises of manufacturers and suppliers to carry out inspections in the course of state control of product safety, which complicates the work of the authorities.
The Ministry considers that the six-month deadline for the imposition of fines and periodic penalty payments is too short to identify the infringement, conduct an investigation and impose a fine.
Also, according to the Ministry, the fines imposed are not sufficiently effective.
In addition, the GOC claimed that the Commission did not provide any evidence that the GOC exercised meaningful control over the conduct of the cooperating exporting producers.
The Ministry of Economy proposed to impose on manufacturers the obligation to properly label the product in order to ensure its traceability in order to facilitate market surveillance authorities in identifying suppliers of non-compliant products.
It is also proposed to grant market surveillance authorities, in the context of official controls on product safety, the right to enter and inspect the premises of economic operators which manufacture or place products on the market.
Fines for violations of the law are to be increased.
A manufacturer, importer or authorised representative who places dangerous products on the market and a distributor who makes them available on the market or provides a dangerous service would be liable to a fine of between EUR 150 and EUR 2 500 (currently between EUR 144 and EUR 1 448).
A fine of between EUR 1 000 and EUR 5 000 (currently between EUR 868 and EUR 4 344) would be imposed if a national consumer protection authority or another market surveillance authority decided to prohibit the placing on the market and supply of dangerous products or the provision of dangerous services.
Failure to comply with the requirement to withdraw dangerous products from the market, recall them from consumers and destroy them would lead to a fine of between EUR 2500 and EUR 6 500 (currently between EUR 1 448 and EUR 5 792).
A fine of between EUR 2 500 and EUR 15 000 (currently between EUR 1 448 and EUR 11584) would be imposed if dangerous products caused damage to the health of consumers.
If a dangerous product caused the death of a consumer, the fine would be between EUR 6 500 and EUR 25 000 (currently between EUR 5 792 and EUR 23 169).
According to the Ministry, in Poland and Austria, infringements of product safety legislation are punishable by fines of up to EUR 25 000 (there is no minimum amount), in Belgium by fines of between EUR 26 000 and EUR 600 000, in Romania by fines of between EUR 155 000 and EUR 6 666, and in Bulgaria by fines of between EUR 125 000 and EUR 7 500.
